    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">Modeling FB | Add Continuous Crank FB</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Heading3_atocs_">Why add a Continuous Crank FB</para>
    <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><table styleclass="PopupTable2" rowcount="1" colcount="1" style="cell-padding:0px; cell-spacing:2px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Body Text">It is often the case, with inverse-kinematics, that the desired motion is applied to a Tool. When the Tool is not driven directly, the driving Part is the input to a mechanism. The motion and forces are transmitted through the mechanism, from the driving Part to the Tool Part.</para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text">Most usually, especially with Cam mechanisms, the driving Part is a Cam-Follower, which is moved by a cam.</para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text">As a special-case, the driving Part may rotate in one direction only, but with a non-uniform rotating speed.</para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text">To make sure this can happen, the driving Part must be the correct length, and it must be instructed to rotate in one direction. This is one application of the <text styleclass="VariableName">Continuous-Crank FB</text>.</para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading3_atocs_">Add CAD Control FB</para>
